### 09--Ethiopia--Outpost_of_Christianity

Ethiopia, a highland, mountainous country associated with the Great Rift Valley, has a rich history spanning over two millennia, making it one of the oldest sites of sustained agriculture in the world. Its strategic location along the Red Sea facilitated early trade, primarily involving ivory, with the outside world. 

The Axumite Kingdom, which emerged around the 1st century AD, was the first significant power in Ethiopia. The kingdom's wealth was derived from agriculture and external trade via the Red Sea port of Adulis. Its language, Ge'ez, laid the foundation for modern Amharic. The Axumites were known for their monumental stone stelae used to mark royal tombs.

In 330-350 AD, under King Ezana (also spelled Izana), Ethiopia officially adopted Christianity, specifically Coptic Christianity, which was influenced by a monophysite belief - the idea of Christ having one divine nature. This conversion was significant as it established Ethiopia as the only substantial Christian stronghold in Africa for over a thousand years until the rise of Islam.

The Zagwe Dynasty (8th-13th centuries) followed, marking an era of Christian expansion and the construction of rock-hewn churches, some of which are considered architectural marvels in sub-Saharan Africa. 

The Solomonic Dynasty, founded in 1270, is perhaps the most famous in Ethiopian history, with its origins mythologically linked to King Solomon and the Queen of Sheba. This dynasty claimed that Menelik, their legendary founder, brought the Ark of the Covenant from Jerusalem, a belief still held by the Ethiopian Orthodox Church despite no archaeological evidence supporting this claim.

Throughout its history, Ethiopia has faced external pressures, including Arab-Muslim encroachments and pastoralist incursions from the south. Despite these challenges, it maintained relative independence due to its geographical isolation and rugged terrain, making it difficult for larger powers to subdue.

In the 19th century, Ethiopia experienced a balance-of-power shift with modernizers like Tewodros II (Theodore II) challenging local nobility. His rule ended tragically in 1868 when he committed suicide during an unsuccessful resistance against a British invasion prompted by the arrest of a British consul.

Ethiopia's most celebrated ruler was Haile Selassie, who reigned from 1930 to 1974. He modernized the country and gained international recognition as a symbol of African pride. However, his rule was marked by autocratic tendencies, leading to his overthrow in 1974 by Marxist military officers. This event marked the end of Ethiopia's 1700-year-old monarchy and initiated a period of civil unrest and secessionist movements.

Ethiopia is unique for its unchallenged change in modern borders following independence, as most African borders were drawn by colonial powers during the 'Scramble for Africa.' The Eritrean region successfully seceded and gained independence in the 1990s. Today, Ethiopia faces numerous challenges typical of many modern African nations.


