Galileo Galilei (1564-1642) was an Italian physicist, mathematician, astronomer, and philosopher who played a significant role in the Scientific Revolution. Born in Pisa, he initially studied medicine at the University of Pisa but found his passion lay in mathematics and physics.

Galileo's early work involved challenging Aristotelian physics, which was the prevailing wisdom of the time. He began experimenting with falling bodies using the Leaning Tower of Pisa, contradicting Aristotle's claim that heavier objects fall faster than lighter ones.

His career took a turn when he moved to Padua in 1592, becoming a professor of mathematics at the University of Padua. Here, he started teaching mechanics and astronomy. It was during this period that he developed an interest in the works of Nicolaus Copernicus, which proposed a heliocentric model of the solar system—a concept that contradicted geocentrism, the widely accepted view at the time.

In 1609, Galileo heard about the Dutch spectacle maker Hans Lippershey's invention - the telescope. He promptly built his own version and began making groundbreaking astronomical discoveries. Using this new tool, he discovered Jupiter's four largest moons (now known as the Galilean moons), the phases of Venus, and sunspots.

These findings supported the Copernican model and conflicted with Aristotelian-Ptolemaic geocentrism, leading to controversy within the scientific community and the Catholic Church. In 1616, under pressure from the Inquisition, Galileo was instructed not to teach or defend the Copernican theory due to its perceived conflict with biblical interpretations.

Despite this warning, Galileo published his 'Sidereus Nuncius' (Starry Messenger) in 1610, detailing his astronomical observations. In 1632, he released 'Dialogue Concerning the Two Chief World Systems', openly advocating for the Copernican model. This led to his trial by the Inquisition and conviction of heresy in 1633.

Galileo was sentenced to house arrest for the remainder of his life, where he continued his scientific work, focusing on physics and mathematics. He completed his most significant work, 'Dialogue Concerning Two New Sciences', just before his death in 1642.

Galileo's contributions were monumental: he developed the scientific method with a strong emphasis on observation and experimentation, promoted mathematical descriptions of natural phenomena, and was one of the first to apply the experimental method systematically to physics and astronomy. His work laid the groundwork for modern science and challenged the Aristotelian worldview, paving the way for the scientific revolution.


