### Tales de Mileto꞉ El sabio filósofo y matemático [Thales of Miletus꞉ The Wise Philosopher and Mathematician] [B072LH86Q2]

Tales of Miletus, often referred to as Tales the Milesian or simply Tales, is considered the first philosopher, known for his pioneering work in rational inquiry about the universe. He is revered as the founder of natural philosophy and one of the seven wise men of Greece.

Born around 624 BCE (the exact date is uncertain) in Miletus, a city on the western coast of Asia Minor (modern-day Turkey), Tales was likely of Phoenician descent. He didn't leave any written works about his scientific discoveries or philosophical views, making historical information gathered from later philosophers and historians like Aristotle, Herodotus, and Diocles Laertius crucial for understanding his life and contributions.

Tales is believed to have traveled to Egypt where he learned geometry from the sacred priests. This learning was then introduced into Greek philosophy. His method of problem-solving often involved broad generalizations and simple inspection or observation, rather than complex mathematical proofs we associate with modern geometry.

As a political advisor to Ionians and Lydians, Tales played a significant role in diplomacy, persuading separate Ionian states to form a federation with Teos as the capital, thereby avoiding war. His practical wisdom was also evident in his business acumen; he predicted an exceptional olive harvest and bought all available presses in Miletus and Kiosk during winter, then leased them out at a premium during harvest season, amassing considerable wealth.

Tales is famous for predicting a solar eclipse in 585 BCE based on his astronomical knowledge. This prediction, following the eclipse, led to a truce between the Medes and Lydians. He also measured the height of Egyptian pyramids using shadows, demonstrating an early form of triangulation, though this claim is subject to historical debate.

Philosophically, Tales posited that water was the fundamental substance from which all things arose – a theory likely influenced by his observations of the Nile's fertility after flooding. He believed Earth floated on an infinite ocean and held that heat resulted from water's movement. This monistic view, attributing all phenomena to one substance (water), set him apart as one of the first thinkers to attempt natural explanations for cosmic phenomena instead of supernatural ones.

Despite limited surviving records, Tales' influence on Greek thought is profound. He's credited with contributing fundamental geometric principles, including the concept that a circle is bisected by any diameter, angles at the base of an isosceles triangle are equal, angles between intersecting lines are equal, two triangles are congruent if they share two angles and a side, and an angle in a semicircle is right.

In summary, Tales of Miletus was a pivotal figure in ancient Greek thought, bridging scientific discovery with philosophical inquiry. His life's work in geometry, astronomy, and natural philosophy laid the groundwork for subsequent Western thought, even if specific details remain obscured by time.


